y as a collective and individual undertaking, makes equal citizenship and individual dignity concrete and transparent, and socializes citizens into their roles as equal political agents. Chapman shows that fully realizing these ends depends not only on the widespread opportunity to vote but also on consistently high levels of actual turnout, and that citizens’ experiences of voting matters as much as the formal properties of a voting system. And these insights are also essential for crafting and evaluating electoral reform proposals.By rethinking what citizens experience when they go to the polls, Election Day recovers the full value of democratic voting today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aDemocracy. 0aElections. 0aVoting. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Process / Campaigns & Elections.2bisacsh  aA Theory of Justice.  aAbstention.  aAcclamation.  aActivism.  aAgainst Democracy.  aArrow's impossibility theorem.  aBallot box.  aBallot.  aBehavioral economics.  aBribery.  aCitizens (Spanish political party).  aCompulsory voting.  aConsequentialism.  aConstitutional amendment.  aCritique.  aDecentralization.  aDeliberation.  aDeliberative democracy.  aDemobilization.  aDictatorship.  aDirect democracy.  aEconomic power.  aElection law.  aElection.  aElectoral fraud.  aElectoral reform.  aElectoral roll.  aElite.  aEthical dilemma.  aFilibuster in the United States Senate.  aFraud.  aFreedom of speech.  aFrench nationality law.  aGabriel Almond.  aGerrymandering.  aGill v. Whitford.  aGovernance.  aHunger strike.  aImpossibility.  aIndication (medicine).  aIndividualism.  aInnovation.  aInstant-runoff voting.  aIrish Catholic.  aJargon.  aJohn Aldrich (political scientist).  aLegitimacy (political).  aLiberalism.  aMaj